			<h3 class="about-page-subtitle">Innovation-Driven Entrepreneurship</h3>
			<p>
				Policymakers and pundits who use entrepreneurship as a catch-all phrase have got it wrong.  There are two distinct forms of entrepreneurship: innovation-driven entrepreneurship (IDE) and small-medium entrepreneurship (SME).  IDEs impact large amounts of people through either innovative technologies or innovative business practices.  They are high risk and high reward.  SMEs are traditional enterprises and they impact smaller amounts of people.  They operate through traditional business models and do not produce new to the world technologies.  
			</p>
			<p>
				REAP focuses on building and accelerating high-growth IDE ecosystems. The REAP program at MIT begins by making this distinction. The program then accelerates the development of entrepreneurial ecosystems through a custom REAP strategy. MIT’s unparalleled excellence in engineering and technology provides REAP teams with a distinct advantage in developing their regional entrepreneurship ecosystems.
			</p>
			<p>
				To learn more about why IDE is different, read the MIT paper, “A Tale of Two Entrepreneurs”
